{{Infobox language |name=Coconuco |nativename=''Namrrik'' |states=[[Colombia]] |region=[[Cauca Department]] |ethnicity=Guambiano (Misak) |speakers=21,000 |date=2008 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Barbacoan languages|Barbacoan]] |lc1=gum|ld1=Guambiano |lc2=ttk|ld2=Totoró |glotto=coco1262 |glottorefname=Coconucan }}
'''Coconuco''' also known as '''Guambiano''' is a [[dialect cluster]] of [[Colombia]] spoken by the [[Guambiano]] indigenous people. Though the three varieties, Guambiano, moribund Totoró, and the extinct Coconuco, are traditionally called languages, Adelaar & Muysken (2004) believe that they are best treated as a single language.
Totoro may be extinct; it had 4 speakers in 1998 out of an ethnic population of 4,000. Guambiano, on the other hand, is vibrant and growing.
Coconucan was for a time mistakenly included in a spurious [[Paezan languages|Paezan]] language family, due to a purported "Moguex" (Guambiano) vocabulary that turned out to be a mix of Páez and Guambiano (Curnow 1998).
== Phonology == The Guambiano inventory is as follows (Curnow & Liddicoat 1998:386).
