'''Dimitris Tsovolas''' ({{lang-el|Δημήτριος Τσοβόλας}}; born 1942) is a Greek [[politician]] who served as [[Ministry of Finance (Greece)|Minister of Finance]] from 1985 to 1989.

==Early life and education==
He was born at [[Melissourgoi]], a village outside [[Arta, Greece|Arta]], [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] in 1942.{{cn|date=August 2018}} He went on to study law at the [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki]]. He worked as a [[lawyer]] in Arta.{{cn|date=August 2018}}

==Political career==
He later began his career in politics as a member of [[Panhellenic Socialist Movement|PASOK]]. He was first elected member of the [[Hellenic Parliament|Parliament]] representing Arta in 1977. He was reelected in 1981 and 1985. He was then elected as an MP for northern [[Athens]].<ref name=bio />

Tsovolas served in the [[Ministry of Finance (Greece)|Ministry of Finance]] in [[Andreas Papandreou]]'s government from 1981 to 1989, serving as a deputy minister from 1981 to 1985, and as the full Minister of Finance from 1985 to 1989.<ref name=bio />

In 1989 he was tried for the so-called [[George Koskotas|Koskotas scandal]] and was sentenced to 2 years in prison and 3 years lack of his political rights. 

In October 1995 he left PASOK and on 20 December that year he founded the [[Democratic Social Movement]].<ref name=bio />

==Personal life==

Tsovolas is married and has two children.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Βιογραφικό|url=http://www.tsovolas.gr/biographiko|website=Dimitris Tsovolas|accessdate=20 September 2015|language=el}}</ref>

==Honours==
He was awarded the highest [[Orden Jugoslavije|Order of the FRY]] from [[Slobodan Milosević]] on 11 December 1999.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vreme.com/arhiva_html/468/02.html |title=Odlikovanja za strance |language=Serbian |author=BETA |newspaper= Vreme |date=December 25, 1999 |accessdate= February 14, 2013}}</ref>

